04290nam a22006495i 9780674037779DE-B159720210421021438.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210421t20212000mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740377797 a10.4159/97806740377792doi  a(DE-B1597)574615  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aHQ1172b.G65 2000eb 7aREL0400302bisacsh04a296.08209732221 aGOLDMAN, Karla, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBeyond the Synagogue Gallery /cKarla GOLDMAN. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2000  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Women and the Synagogue -- t1 Jewish Women: Acculturation in Old and New Worlds -- t2 Women's Emergence in the Early American Synagogue Community -- t3 The Quest for Respectability: Mixed Choirs and Family Pews -- t4 The Trouble with Jewish Women -- t5 Women in the Reforming Synagogue: Resistance and Transformation -- t6 Kaufmann Kohler and the Ideal Jewish Woman -- t7 Beyond the Gallery: American Jewish Women in the 1890s -- tEpilogue: Twentieth-Century Resonances -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBeyond the Synagogue Gallery recounts the emergence of new roles for American Jewish women in public worship and synagogue life. Karla Goldman's study of changing patterns of female religiosity is a story of acculturation, of adjustments made to fit Jewish worship into American society. Goldman focuses on the nineteenth century. This was an era in which immigrant communities strove for middle-class respectability for themselves and their religion, even while fearing a loss of traditions and identity. For acculturating Jews some practices, like the ritual bath, quickly disappeared. Women's traditional segregation from the service in screened women's galleries was gradually replaced by family pews and mixed choirs. By the end of the century, with the rising tide of Jewish immigration from Russia and Eastern Europe, the spread of women's social and religious activism within a network of organizations brought collective strength to the nation's established Jewish community. Throughout these changing times, though, Goldman notes persistent ambiguous feelings about the appropriate place of women in Judaism, even among reformers. This account of the evolving religious identities of American Jewish women expands our understanding of women's religious roles and of the Americanization of Judaism in the nineteenth century; it makes an essential contribution to the history of religion in America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Apr 2021) 0aJewish womenzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aJudaismzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aWomen in JudaismzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674037779423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674037779.jpg  a978-3-11-044220-5  HUP eBook Package Backlist 2005-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK